Regarding the gaps: 

> no `partial impl` yet;

This should be pretty easy to add in a follow-up, given the infrastructure laid by this PR.

> no specialization on inherent impls;

I'm really not sure about this one; right now, inherent impls work pretty independently from our trait infrastructure, so this is potentially a major refactor. It's also one of the more subtle bits of the design. I think we should probably sit on this for a while.

> no support for `default` with associated consts;

Should be easy to add; can probably sneak it into this PR.

> no support for specializing based on trait hierarchies (super traits).

I'm not actually sure why this isn't working yet; somehow the selection infrastructure is failing to elaborate supertrait relationships. Probably an easy fix?

Here's a concise example of a problem I've found.

This code compiles fine:

``` rust
use std::marker::PhantomData;

trait Id_ {
    type Out;
}

type Id<T> = <T as Id_>::Out;

impl<T> Id_ for T {
    type Out = T;
}

fn coerce<A>(_: PhantomData<A>, x: A) -> A { x }

#[test]
fn test() {
    type Bool = Id<bool>;
    let x = coerce(PhantomData::<Bool>, true);
}
```

But this, with the only difference being the "default" keyword, does not:

``` rust
use std::marker::PhantomData;

trait Id_ {
    type Out;
}

type Id<T> = <T as Id_>::Out;

impl<T> Id_ for T {
    default type Out = T;
}

fn coerce<A>(_: PhantomData<A>, x: A) -> A { x }

#[test]
fn test() {
    type Bool = Id<bool>;
    let x = coerce(PhantomData::<Bool>, true);
}
```

The error reported is "associated type expected, found bool" in the second argument to the call to `coerce`.

For example, this code gets the ICE:

``` rust
trait Foo {
    type Out;
}

impl Foo for bool {
    type Out = ();
}

impl<T> Foo for T {
    default type Out = bool;
}
```

Hi, I have been looking at this feature with interest since it would hopefully also open up for some more generic programming. Today I decided to try it out (since the RFC landed and all) and checked out 7e76e87 and compiled it.

After some testing I ran into a somewhat odd issue regarding traits with type-parameters. It might be that I am misunderstanding some of the rules in the RFC, but I am a bit confused as to why the following does not work (I am getting a conflict here):

``` rust
struct Data;

trait Foo<T> {}
trait Bar<T> {}

impl<T, U> Bar<U> for T    where T: Foo<U> {}
impl<U>    Bar<U> for Data {}
```

while the following will work:

``` rust
struct Data;

trait Foo {}
trait Bar {}

impl<T> Bar for T    where T: Foo {}
impl    Bar for Data {}
```

Wouldn't the specific `impl<U> Bar<U> for Data` be more specific than the generic `impl` for `T: Foo<U>`?

One teeny little issue:

``` Rust
#![feature(specialization)]

trait Coerce<U> {
    fn coerce(self) -> Option<U>;
}

impl<U,V> Coerce<U> for V {
    default fn coerce(self) -> Option<U> { None }
}

impl<U> Coerce<U> for U {
    fn coerce(self) -> Option<U> { Some(self) }
}

fn coerce<V, U>(v: V) -> Option<U> {
    <V as Coerce<U>>::coerce(v)
}

fn coerce_lifetime<'a, 'b, T>(t: &'a T) -> &'b T {
    coerce(t).unwrap()
}

fn main() {
    let a = String::from("hello");

    let bomb = coerce_lifetime(&a);
    drop(a);
    println!("{}", bomb);
}

```

This crashes pretty nicely.

I did talk about this in the RFC - this obviously has to be fixed somehow + test.

@m4rw3r 

The scenario you're describing isn't actually a specialization: there's no particular relationship between `Data` and `T: Foo`. The reason that the version without generics works is that the compiler can see that there's no overlap, because `Data` doesn't impl `Foo`, and everything involved is crate-local. But with type parameters, downstream crates could impl `Foo<T>` for their own types. See the [rebalancing coherence RFC](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/1023) for more details.

(In general, specialization works when there _is_ overlap, but one impl is "contained within" another -- roughly, the `where` clause for one impl implies everything in the `where` clause for the other. The RFC gives a lot more detail.)

