Cross-posting from the RFC issue for visibility (it's probably more suited to this issue anyway):

@aturon @nikomatsakis 
Here's something to think about. This is using the current implementation. This shows a compile-time dependency on the hidden type of a `default`ed associated type. Whether this is relying on behaviour not valid according to the RFC is another matter.

``` rust
fn main() {
    enum Undefined {}
    trait Opaque {
        type Out;
    }
    impl<T> Opaque for T {
        default type Out = Undefined;
    }
    impl Opaque for () {
        type Out = bool;
    }

    trait Same<A, B> {
        type T;
        fn cast(a: A) -> B;
    }
    impl<A> Same<A, A> for () {
        type T = A;
        fn cast(a: A) -> A {
            a
        }
    }
    fn cast<X, Y>(x: X) -> Y where (): Same<X, Y> {
        <() as Same<X, Y>>::cast(x)
    }

    // Bool is an "opaque" type that is secretly bool
    // This will not work: let x: Bool = true;
    type Bool = <() as Opaque>::Out;

    // But the following does work:

    // compilation dependency:
    {
        fn foo<X, Y>(y: Y) where (): Same<X, Y> {

        }
        let x: bool = true;
        foo::<Bool, _>(x); // only compiles when Bool is bool
        // also, if Bool is not bool, the compilation error message will reported the normalised type
    }
    // getting a bool from a Bool works
    {
        let x: Bool = unimplemented!(); // a Bool
        let x: bool = cast(x); // x is now a bool, at compile time, requires Bool == bool
    }
    // getting a Bool from a bool won't compile though
    {
        let x: bool = true;
        let x: Bool = cast(x); // doesn't compile
    }
}
```

@dylanede is this the same example you posted on the rust-lang/rfcs#1210? If so, there is a bug, but it is not the compilation time dependency -- it's rather the error on the last line, which is a bit perplexing (likely a missing normalization).

It is expected that you can project `<() as Opaque>::Out>` to `bool` -- this is because the impl for `()` defined `type Out = bool` without the keyword `default`. What would be a bug is if the keyword `default` were used there.

The case that we were debating was this one:
- If the most specific impl for the type you have uses `default` (not the case in your example);
- but there cannot be a more specific impl (because of orphan rules);
- should we allow you to rely on the type or not?

The answer to _that_ question should be no.

So, in your example, if I project `<u16 as Opaque>::Out` I should _not_ get `Undefined` (or at least should not be able to rely on it).

@dylanede 

Turns out the problem you raised is actually an existing normalization bug for type aliases, unrelated to specialization:

``` rust
fn main() {
    enum Undefined {}
    trait Opaque {
        type Out;
    }
    impl Opaque for () {
        type Out = bool;
    }
    type Bool = <() as Opaque>::Out;
    let x: <() as Opaque>::Out = true; // works
    let x: Bool = true; // fails
}
```
